data: A standard ProSlide CannonBowl slide in Swirl City.
A set of four mat slides, located on the east side of Barracuda Bay. Located where Shipwreck Falls now stands.
A large family wave pool located past Hook's Lagoon where Adventure Land for Kids used to be.

Four inner tube water slides (two enclosed, two open). Replaced the Rainbow Mountain slide complex on the north side of Barracuda Bay. For many years, the end slides were black and the middle slides were white. In 2010, the slides were repainted to blue, green, yellow, and teal. The area has also taken on the popular use of the Barracuda Bay name since the removal of most of the original complex.
Cascading Lazy River on the west side of the former Barracuda Bay.
Basic Lazy River south of the Swirl City complex.
Five story tall water playground with slides, and a dump bucket. Stands roughly where the Tadpole Island kiddie pool in Adventure Land for Kids was.
The original water slides and the first slides at Darien Lake. Once located over the main lake. Rebuilt on the south side of Barracuda Bay in the 1990 as Torpedo Rapids.
A small wave pool connected to Flotation Station.
A water slide that features three "Topsy-Turvy" funnels and varying grades of track located in the Swirl City complex.
A yellow enclosed water slide located in Barracuda Bay with a rainbow colored inside.
A set of four mat slides on the north side of the hill which was incorporated into Barracuda Bay in 1990. Replaced by 'Cuda Falls in 1994.
A raft water slide located that was located in Barracuda Bay with a "wavy" look.
Small kids playground pool that was located in Adventure Land for Kids. Replaced by Hook's Lagoon in 1996.

Moncton Muslim association was formed in 2000. The goal of the association was to serve the needs of local Muslim community. Within 5 years association was able to build a mosque, the first and only mosque in the Greater Moncton area. Current goal of the association is to run the Mosque, provide opportunities of Islamic learning, facilitate social events and help local Muslim community as well as the general community of Moncton.

*A 14 story building run by the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community and predominantly inhabbited by Ahmadis making up 98 percent of the nearly 150 families living in the building. A hall on the first floor of the building serves as the gathering center for the local chapter.
local mosque for the Ahmadi Muslim Community's local chapter; It was bought as a church and converted to a mosque. .

A converted Mosque from a Dutch style castle was brought by a member of the Jamaat in 2005 and later donated to the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community to serve as Mosque and center for the local chapters of Oshawa and Durham. The property includes a 25 acre plot and has also regularly used by the Jamaat for regional sports events. The opening of the Masjid Al Mahdi took place in July 2006 during the visit of Khalifatul Masih the fifth to Canada.

a primary school building which includes a Gym, several class rooms and small school field in the back lot was bought by the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community. The Masjid serves as the local Ahmadiyya Muslim chapter.

The center also serves as the regional center for the community in GTA East.
serves as the Mosque for the Local Ahmadiyya Muslim Chapters of Hamilton South and Hamilton North.

The center serves as a Prayer space and auxiliary function to the local Ahmadiyya Muslim Chapter of Cornwall.

When Candace sees what her brothers are doing, her maternal instincts emerge and she agrees to help, on the condition that they don't use any technological means whatsoever (like incubators, etc.). Meanwhile, Doofenshmirtz plots revenge on whales who told his girlfriend to dump him by means of a whale translation device he created.

Meanwhile, Dr. Doofenshmirtz tries to create traffic jams with a duplication device.
